Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @shallot{1}. Drain and rinse @chickpeas{1}; dry
thoroughly with #paper towels{}. Halve, core, and dice @apple{1} into ½-inch
pieces.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add
shallot and chickpeas; season with @garlic powder{1%tsp}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.
Cook, stirring occasionally, until chickpeas are warmed through and browned in
spots, ~{2-4%minutes}. Transfer to a #plate{} to cool.

> TIP: It's natural for chickpeas to pop a bit; lower heat if needed.

Meanwhile, remove and discard any large stems from @kale{4%oz}; chop into
bite-size pieces.

Place kale in a #large bowl{}. Using your hands, massage with a large drizzle of
@olive oil{3%tsp} until leaves are tender, ~{1-2%minutes} (similar to how you
would knead dough).

> TIP: Don't skip this step—massaging helps the kale leaves wilt slightly,
> lending a tender (never fibrous!) texture.

In a #small bowl{}, whisk together @balsamic vinegar{5%tsp}, @Dijon mustard{2%tsp},
@olive oil{3%tsp}, and @sugar{1/4%tsp}.

> For 4 servings, use 6 TBSP olive oil and ½ tsp sugar.

Add @mixed greens{2%oz}, shallot and chickpeas, apple, and @feta cheese{1/2%cup}
to bowl with kale. Drizzle with as much dressing as you like; toss to combine.

Divide salad between bowls and garnish with @dried cranberries{1%oz}. Serve.

> TIP: Taking it to go? Refrigerate prepared ingredients in separate containers,
> then toss when ready to eat.